occurrences.line_text: One prison fittest is to hold vs two:
Gainst one that hath both wronged you, and vs:
So shall you by one gift saue all vs three aliue.
That makes me feare in time he will vs quite forsake.
But not for it this ods twixt vs doth stand,
To bide what iudgement ye shall vs afford.
Who yesterday droue vs to such distresse,
Some place shall vs receiue, and harbour yield;
And purchase it to vs with speare and shield:
Did set vppon vs flying both for feare:
Please it you Ladie, to vs to aread,
So passed we, till this young man vs met,
And bring vs bale and bitter sorrowings,
When day is spent, and rest vs needeth most,
Haue not vouchsaft to graunt vnto vs twaine
What hope of helpe doth then for vs remaine,
If that no salues may vs to health restore?
Aread good sire, some counsell, that may vs sustaine.
The which for promise of great meed, vs draue
That so rich frute should be from vs bereft;
They teach vs, how to each degree and kynde
That good should from vs goe, then come in greater store.
Spoyld all our cots, and caried vs from hence?
There leaue we them in ioy, and let vs tell
Full of the makers guile, with vsage sly
Both what she was, and what that vsage ment,
Vnworthy vsage of redoubted knight.
That through continuall practise and vsage,
O goodly vsage of those antique times,
All ciuill vsage and gentility,
The diuerse vsage and demeanure daint,
That both were bent t'auenge his vsage base,
And wearie limmes recur'd after late vsage bad.
Whose cursed vsage and vngodly trade
At which his vncouth guise and vsage quaint
Fallen into that Tyrants hand and vsage bad.
But that those villens through their vsage bad
For his faire vsage and conditions sound,
But put away proud looke, and vsage sterne,
Towards a Ladie, whom with vsage kind
Him of vngentle vsage did [re]proue
By gentle vsage of that wretched Dame.
Seeing his royall vsage and array,
Of all the vile demeane, and vsage bad,
With such queint vsage, fit for Queenes and Kings,
From the worldes eye, and from her right vsaunce?
With whom he whoredome vsd, that few did know,
To proofe of passing wonders hath full often vsd.
In which she often vsd from open heat
And vsd to bath themselues in that deceiptfull shade.
Thereof she vsd to giue to drinke to each,
Was vsd of Knights and Ladies seeming gent:
And vsd the same in battell aye to beare;
He vs'd to slug, or sleepe in slothfull shade:
Such vs'd wise Glauce to that wrathfull knight,
But speare and curtaxe both vsd Priamond in field.
What time she vsd to liue in wiuely sort;
But layd aside, when so she vsd her looser sport.
And to the present neede it wisely vsd.
Is now hight vertue, and so vs'd of all:
Since he himselfe it vs'd in that great fight
But vsd to fish for fooles on the dry shore,
Which long he vsd with carefull diligence,
To search out those, that vsd to rob and steale,
But Talus vsde in times of ieopardy
Thereto they vsde one most accursed order,
But vsde him friendly for further intent,
That neuer vsde to liue by plough nor spade,
And him no lesse, that any like did vse,
But he could not them vse, but kept them still in store.
As was his vse, ofttimes to visit me:
As miserable louers vse to rew,
As sparckles from the Anduile vse to fly,
Then when as vse of speach was from her reft,
She to her vse returnd, and streight defyde
What bootes it all to haue, and nothing vse?
If then thee list my offred grace to vse,
To couet more, then I haue cause to vse?
To teach them how to vse their present state.
To vse that sword so wisely as it ought.
But vse thy fortune, as it doth befall,
And others it to vse according to his kind.
Let later age that noble vse enuie,
As pleased them to vse, that vse it might:
As pleased them to vse, that vse it might:
Did vse to hide, and plaine apparaunce shonne:)
So thought this Mayd (as maydens vse to done)
Ill weares he armes, that nill them vse for Ladies sake.
And curteise vse conceiu'd affection bace,
Ne how to speake, ne how to vse his gest,
In beastly vse that I did euer find;
She cast to vse, both fit for hard emprize;
And vse of awfull Maiestie remoue:
And seruing her in her malitious vse,
Which she by art could vse vnto her will,
And throughly skild in vse of shield and speare;
And not for vertuous vse, which some doe tell
But call ye me the Saluage Knight, as others vse.
And threw away, with vow to vse no more,
Thus long this gentle bird to him did vse,
That will not vse his gifts for thanklesse nigardise.
Blessed the man that well can vse his blis:
And many herbes did vse. But when as nought
But to the antique vse, which was of yore,
But there the Paynim, who that vse well knew
So ought each Knight, that vse of perill has,
Right true: but faulty men vse oftentimes
But like a rebell stout I will him vse.
He list no lenger to vse lothfull speach,
And practicke vse in armes: ne spared not
Which they now hackt & hewd, as if such vse they hated,
Her name Mercilla most men vse to call;
Which vncouth vse when as the Prince perceiued,
So also did this Monster vse like slight
The vse of armes, and battell quite forgone:
In these strange waies, where neuer foote did vse,
Which he could wisely vse, and well apply,
A shamefull vse as euer I did heare,
Onely the vse of armes, which most I ioy,
I may beare armes, and learne to vse them right;
Ne knew the vse of warlike instruments,
Who hauing now no vse of his long speare,
Whose vertue he by vse well vnderstood:
Did vse, his feeble body to sustaine;
Vse scanted diet, and forbeare your fill,
Maintaine this euill vse, thy foes thereby to foile.
The one or th'other, better her to vse:
And saw those villaines her so vildely vse,
Be well aware, how ye the same doe vse,
As they doe know each can most aptly vse.
And sad Repentance vsed to embay
Wherein she vsed hath the practicke paine
Who vsed in a darksome inner bowre
Ne euer may be vsed by his fone,
Who him at first well vsed euery way;
And to their purpose vsed wicked art:
Had vsed bene of that foolehardy Squire;
First she him sought in Court, where most he vsed
Into his powre, that vsed her so hard,
On horsebacke vsed Triamond to fight,
With curtaxe vsed Diamond to smite,
Thereto the villaine vsed craft in fight;
For other beds the Priests there vsed none,
With which she vsed still to tye her fone;
Therefore she vsed often to resort,
A Damzell vsed vylde:
His hope of refuge vsed to remaine.
Which hauing got, he vsed without crime
Her selfe to pleasaunce, vsed to resort
She vsed most to keepe her royall court,
Which had approued bene in vses manifold.
On them she workes her will to vses bad:
To such vaine vses, that him best became:
Of vertue and of ciuill vses lore,
For other vses, then they them translated;
Which warlike vses had deuiz'd of yore.
For that it there most vseth to abound;
To come of him, for vsing her so hard,
The vsuall ioyes at knitting of loues band.
But beare him farre from hope of succour vsuall.
For no no vsuall fire, no vsuall rage
For no no vsuall fire, no vsuall rage
Vpon his vsuall beast it firmely bound,
But he him selfe, through practise vsuall,
And what I cannot quite, requite with vsuree.
Accursed vsurie was all his trade,
And taking vsurie of time forepast,
But did vsurpe with wrong and tyrannie
And it vsurped by vnrighteous doome:
Th'vsurped crowne, as if that he were wood,
Vsurpt the crowne, during their pupillage;
Which they had long vsurpt; and them restoring
Did life with vsury to him restore,
And vsury withall: such gaine was gotten deare.
To haue supplyde the first, and paide the vsury.
vThat doest not know the least thing of them all?
Ambrose and Vther did ripe years attaine,
After him Vther, which Pendragon hight,
Ye see that good king Vther now doth make
Which Vther with those forrein Pagans held,
from Brute to Vthers rayne.
And thrilling sorrow throwne his vtmost dart;
In these sad words she spent her vtmost breath:
But ere they did their vtmost obsequy,
And groneth out his vtmost grudging spright,
Came to a riuer, by whose vtmost brim
Did stretch themselues without the vtmost bound
Assembling all his force and vtmost might,
And spred his empire to the vtmost shore,
Corineus had that Prouince vtmost west,
Nigh to his vtmost date he saw proceed,
Till they outraigned had their vtmost date,
And th'vtmost meanes of victorie assay,
Or th'vtmost issew of his owne decay.
To draw their boate within the vtmost bound
That th'vtmost sandy breach they shortly fetch,
Shall to the vtmost mountaines fly apace:
Who dyes the vtmost dolour doth abye,
Into the vtmost Angle of the world he knew.
Therewith resolu'd to proue her vtmost might,
The vtmost rowme, and past the formest dore,
The vtmost rowme, abounding with all precious store.
Her loue, her seruice, and her vtmost wealth.
And know the measure of their vtmost date,
To draw their dayes vnto the vtmost date,
But that his vtmost prowesse there made knowen,
Thinking to worke on her his vtmost wracke,
I me resolu'd the vtmost end to proue,
She staid not the vtmost end thereof to try,
For dread of her displeasures vtmost proofe.
That battels vtmost triall to aduenter.
For after that the vtmost date, assynde
But lastly to make proofe of vtmost shame,
From th'vtmost brinke of the Armericke shore,
Thinking the vtmost of their force to trie,
But th'vtmost end perforce for to aby,
Had left that couple, nere their vtmost cast.
Ere long enforst to breath his vtmost blast,
A full good pecke within the vtmost brim,
The inner garment fret, not th'vtter touch;
As vnto her to vtter his desire;
Till to the Bridges vtter gate I came:
To worke his vtter shame, and throughly him confound.
Vtterers of secrets he from thence debard,
For all his power was vtterly defaste,
Till vengeance vtterly the guilt bereaue:
And th'idle breath all vtterly exprest:
That thy sad people vtterly fordonne,
Now vanisht vtterly, and cleane subuerst
And now it is so vtterly decayd,
Had vtterly subuerted his vnrighteous state.
Who then with vtt'rance graue, and count'nance sad
And wanted grace in vtt'ring of the same,
Her husband Vulcan whylome for her sake,
To dry them selues by Vulcanes flaming light,
With liquid waues, fiers Vulcans rage to tame,
Th'amazed vulgar tels of warres and mortall fight.
Betweene the vulgar and the noble seed,
Were heap'd together with the vulgar sort,
And to the vulgar beckning with his hand,
Bred in assemblies of the vulgar sort,
Vnto the vulgar for good gold insted,
Therefore the vulgar did about him flocke,
So feeble skill of perfect things the vulgar has.
And all the vulgar did about them throng,
And Tityus fed a vulture on his maw;
As when a Vulture greedie of his pray,
VVhilest Melibee is slaine:
That called was the VVhirlepoole of decay,
VVhose euer be the shield, faire Amoret be his.
Her name was VVomanhood, that she exprest
Euen in the lap of VVomanhood there sate,
And him beside rides fierce reuenging VVrath,
Full many mischiefes follow cruell VVrath;
Such one was VVrath, the last of this vngodly tire.
Prouokt with VVrath, and Enuies false surmise,
Most mercilesse of women, VVyden hight,
But for vyld treasons, and outrageous shame,
In hand of leachour vylde.
A Damzell vsed vylde:
Some one, whose tongue was for his trespasse vyle
This wofull tale? or how those Brigants vyle,
And round about, as she could well it vze,
Vertue giues her selfe light, through darkenesse for to wade.
Thus in still waues of deepe delight to wade,
Through which it was vneath for wight to wade;
Ne durst assay to wade the perlous seas,
And wade in doubt, what best were to be donne:
As that in riuers swim, or brookes doe wade.
That ouer shoes in bloud he waded on the ground.
Of the cold liquor, which he waded in,
And wading through the waues with stedfast sway,
And strongly wading through the waues vnused,
Which neither able were to wag, or once to weld.
That lim he could not wag. Thence he him lad,
But th'Elfin knight, which ought that warlike wage,
Thou that doest liue in later times, must wage
With all their force, and battell strong to wage
And to be seene, as his most worthie wage,
As if her life vpon the wager lay,
That lately turneyd, had the wager wonne:
Is not (I wager) Florimell at all;
And after all, vpon the wagon beame
Then to her yron wagon she betakes,
In westerne waues his wearie wagon did recure.
His weary wagon to the Westerne vale,
She to her wagon clombe; clombe all the rest,
Whiles they the corse into her wagon reare,
By this the Northerne wagoner had set
And right and wrong ylike in equall ballaunce waide.
Through many perils wonne, and many fortunes waide.
She could deuise, and thousand waies inuent,
Full many waies she sought, but none could find,
They both vprose, and to their waies them dight:
Yet many waies to enter may be found,
And through the thickest makes her nighest waies;
Had it defaste; thenceforth reformd her waies,
Either through gifts, or guile, or such like waies,
And wooed him by all the waies she could:
The waies, through which my weary steps I guyde,
In these strange waies, where neuer foote did vse,
Or how to issue forth in waies vntryde,
And tryde all waies, how each mote entrance make
Of so long waies to him befallen late.
But go thy waies to him, and fro me say,
And weary of this worlds vnquiet waies,
Yet ceast he not to sew and all waies proue,
For that a waift, the which by fortune came
But yours the waift by high prerogatiue.
That his owne waight his necke asunder broke,
And after she had wept and wail'd a space,
With that she wept and wail'd, as if her hart
Then gan she waile and weepe, to see that woefull stowre.
Staid not to waile his woefull funerall,
And in the way as she did weepe and waile,
My last left comfort is, my woes to weepe and waile.
And all about it wandring ghostes did waile and howle.
The damned ghosts, that doe in torments waile,
In which full many soules do endlesse waile and weepe.
And often waile their wealth, which he from them did keepe.
But who that liues, is left to waile his losse:
Where wicked ghosts do waile their former sin.
As pittying to see her waile and weepe;
Then gan she loudly cry, and weepe, and waile,
He wailed womanlike with many a teare,
But alwaies wept and wailed night and day,
Then waste in woe and wailefull miserie.
Where many soules sit wailing woefully,
Yet wist not what their wailing ment, yet did
From her nigh wearie waine, and in her armes
O Titan, haste to reare thy ioyous waine:
And lose the teme out of his weary waine,
Now when as Phoebus with his fiery waine
And for her Dwarfe, that wont to wait each houre;
And watch the noyous night, and wait for ioyous day.
Eftsoones the Gard, which on his state did wait,
And thousand furies wait on wrathfull sword;
The gate was open, but therein did wait
As if they lay in wait, or else themselues did hide.
Nor ward to wait at morne and euening late,
Where earely waite him many a gazing eye,
That lay in waite her wrack for to bewaile,
After she long in waite for me did lye,
On whom I waite to wreake that foule despight,
Did waite about it, gaping griesly all begor'd.
Guarded with many damzels, that did waite
Lying in waite, how him he damadge might.
Vpon a day as they the time did waite,
And when she wakt, he waited diligent,
A noble crew about them waited round
Which long hath waited by the Stygian strond.
And bold, as euer Squire that waited by knights side.
Thus she there waited vntill euentyde,
And with meet seruice waited him about;
Did on the Thamis attend, and waited well
Which on her waited, things amisse to mend,
For his returne, she waited had for nought,
Misfortune waites aduantage to entrap
Still waites for death with dread and trembling aw;
There waiting long, to win the wished sight
Which still sate waiting on that wastfull clift,
The ruefull Strich, still waiting on the bere,
Waiting aduauntage on the pray to sease;
The Sprite then gan more boldly him to wake,
Still did he wake, and still did watch for dawning light.
But praying still did wake, and waking did lament.
By this the good Sir Satyrane gan wake
Two eyes him needeth, for to watch and wake,
And therefore prayd her wake, to heare him plaine.
Vnder his side him nipt, that forst to wake,
Looke vp at last, and wake thy dulled spirit,
Now ye haue made my heart to wake alway,
Now will ye sleepe? ah wake, and rather weepe,
Or suffer her out of her sleepe to wake,
As one out of a dreame not waked well,
Her selfe downe soust, she waked out of dread
Like one that from his dreame is waked suddenlye.
With that she waked, full of fearefull fright,
Till being waked with these loud alarmes,
Which when the wakeful Elfe perceiu'd, streight way
And wakefull dogges before them farre do lye,
The wakefull dogs did neuer cease to bay,
And wakefull watches euer to abide:
Nor brasen walls, nor many wakefull spyes,
An hony combe, the wakefull dogs espy,
Ere he had slept his fill, he wakened were,
Whom suddenly he wakes with fearefull frights,
The Damzell wakes, then all attonce vpstart,
Her, whom he waking euermore did weene,
But praying still did wake, and waking did lament.
For feare of waking him, his lips bedewd,
To thinke of your nights want, that should yee waking keepe.
But gently waking them, gaue them the time of day.
And when she wakt, he waited diligent,
Whether she slept or wakt, with her soft hand
And would haue wakt the Satyre by her syde;
That when he wak't out of his warelesse paine,
Then when she wakt, they all gaue one consent,
In homely wize, and wald with sods around,
Then with a few to walke the rightest way;
To walke this way in Pilgrims poore estate.
Her other leg was lame, that she no'te walke,
And euer as she went, her tongue did walke
And with like labour walke the world around,
To walke the woods with that his Idole faire,
The greene-wood long did walke, and wander wide
Which punish wicked men, that walke amisse:
And walke about her gardens of delight,
And graunt more scope to me to walke at large.
But making way for death at large to walke:
Both plaine, and pleasant to be walked in,
And through the Hall there walked to and fro
In this sad plight he walked here and there,
Whiles through the world she walked in this sort,
To sit and rest the walkers wearie shankes,
Does shew to him, that walkes in feare and sad affright.
And all without were walkes and alleyes dight,
And to thy will abuse? Thou walkest free,
And walketh forth without suspect of crime:
But restlesse walketh all the world around,
When walking through the Gardin, them she spyde,
Now walking soft, now sitting still vpright,
From euery coast that heauen walks about,
Walkt in that forest, whom he had not taught
Walkt round about the world, and I no lesse,
But walkt each where, for feare of hid mischaunce,
Walkt through the wood, for pleasure, or for need;
And therein thousand payres of louers walkt,
But walkt abrode, and round about did rome,
A while she walkt, and chauft; a while she threw
But walkt about them euer and anone,
Forth ryding vnderneath the castell wall,
Where fast embard in mightie brasen wall,
He marched forth towards that castle wall;
Vnto the watchman on the castle wall;
And wind his horne vnder the castle wall,
First she them led vp to the Castle wall,
With many raunges reard along the wall;
But Elfiline enclosd it with a golden wall.
Within this castle wall a Ladie faire,
A brasen wall in compas to compile
Vntill that brasen wall they vp doe reare:
And to them calling from the castle wall,
Him follow'd Yar, soft washing Norwitch wall,
That Romaine Monarch built a brasen wall,
Vppon the Castle wall, and when she saw
And powred forth ouer the Castle wall,
Ouer the Castle wall adowne her cast,
Hemd in with waters like a wall in sight;
Where sounding loud a Trumpet from the wall,
Vnto the wall his way did fearelesse take,
Vppon their wall good watch and ward did keepe.
But ryding streight vnder the Castle wall,
Which there stood gazing from the Citties wall
They from the wall him seeing so aghast,
There where she stood vppon the Castle wall,
And wall'd by nature gainst inuaders wrong,
For wall'd it was with waues, which rag'd and ror'd
As still are wont t'annoy the walled towne,
That bloud-red billowes like a walled front
The yron walles to ward their blowes are weake & fraile.
Whom I from far see on the walles appeare
Deepe in their flesh, quite through the yron walles,
The walles so stoutly with their sturdie maine,
And girt in with two walles on either side;
So like, that all the walles did seeme to flame.
And all about, the glistring walles were hong
That through the yron walles their way they rent,
And eeke this wallet at your backe arreare,
Did wallow in all other fleshly myre,
All wallowd in his owne fowle bloudy gore,
All wallowd in his owne yet luke-warme blood,
He tombled on an heape, and wallowd in his gore.
That he lay wallowd all in his owne gore.
In her owne blood all wallow'd wofully,
By which there lay a knight all wallowed
Nor brasen walls, nor many wakefull spyes,
And all within the riuen walls were hung
Where now enclosd in wooden wals full faste,
Whose wals were high, but nothing strong, nor thick,
Whose wals and towres were builded high and strong
Both roofe, and floore, and wals were all of gold,
Thence brought th[m] to the second roome, whose wals
Yet were the wals, that did the same vphold,
The ruin'd wals he did reï¿½ fÂ¦difye
The wals were round about apparelled
No fort so fensible, no wals so strong,
For round about, the wals yclothed were
That makes the wals to stagger with astonishment:
And sad to view his visage pale and wan,
Which he by many rash aduentures wan,
Speake they, which haue beheld the battailes, which it wan.
In their beginning they are weake and wan,
Crying with pitteous voice, and count'nance wan;
His forlorne steed from him the victour wan;
He seemed breathlesse, hartlesse, faint, and wan,
And those with which th'EubÃ¦an young man wan
That vitall powres gan wexe both weake and wan,
Who soone by meanes thereof the Empire wan,
As pale and wan as ashes was his looke,
